export function composeTemplateBundle() {
  return "# Base Skill\n\nRead the repo's docs, config, and nearby code before editing.\nUse the repo vocabulary: skill, plan, agent brief, and boundary rule.\nIf the change spans multiple files or concepts, write a plan before editing.\nStay inside the boundary rule. Do not edit files outside the allowed surface.\nUse `handoff()` for work that should remain engineer-owned.\nRun the relevant validation before you say the work is done.\nWhen the repo needs tracker output, keep the agent brief portable and let the adapter handle export details.\n\n# Git Workflow\n\nCheck `git status` before you edit.\nDo not overwrite unrelated work.\nMake focused commits when a task is done.\nUse clear commit messages that describe the user-visible change.\nIf the repo already has a branch or release convention, follow it.\n\n# Handoff Workflow\n\nUse `handoff()` when the work should not be implemented in this repo now.\nCreate the handoff in the same file where the deferred work appears.\nMake the handoff object explicit. Include the title, description, fallback, and the repo-local context needed to finish later.\nKeep the fallback safe and local. It should preserve the current UI state and avoid hidden side effects.\nIf the deferred work crosses a tracker boundary, keep the payload tracker-neutral and let the adapter handle export format.\n\n# Linear Handoff\n\nUse this template when the repo exports agent briefs to Linear.\nWrite a short, complete brief that another engineer can act on without reading the whole thread.\nInclude the title, context, boundary rule, acceptance, files touched, and any blocker that needs a follow-up.\nKeep the brief portable. Do not put tracker-specific syntax in the core content.\nUse the adapter only at export time.\n\n# Plan and Execute\n\nUse this template when a change spans multiple files or concepts.\nRead the repo's docs, config, and nearby code before you edit anything.\nWrite the plan first.\nBreak the work into small tasks that each produce one testable result.\nKeep each task inside the boundary rule.\nUse the repo's validation workflow after each task that can be verified locally.\nUpdate the plan as you finish tasks.\n\n# State Boundaries\n\nTreat the boundary rule as a hard line.\nEdit local UI and local state only.\nDo not move network access, persistence, or shared state into a component when the repo keeps that work elsewhere.\nIf a change needs state outside the boundary rule, create a handoff instead of widening the edit.\nWhen a file already depends on shared state, keep the change local to the allowed surface and preserve the existing boundary.\n\n# Validation Workflow\n\nRun the relevant local validation before you say the work is done.\nPrefer the narrowest command that exercises the files you changed.\nIf a validation step fails, fix the failure before moving on.\nRecord the command you ran when you hand the work off.\nDo not treat a manual spot check as a substitute for validation.";
}
